{"title_page": "Cadillac Records", "text_new": "{{short description|2008 musical biopic directed by Darnell Martin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Cadillac Records\n| image = Cadillac records poster.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darnell Martin]]\n| producer = [[Sofia Sondervan]]<br/>Andrew Lack\n| writer = [[Darnell Martin]]\n| narrator = [[Cedric the Entertainer]]\n| starring = [[Adrien Brody]]<br/>[[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]<br />[[Jeffrey Wright]]<!--per poster-->\n| music = [[Terence Blanchard]]<br/>[[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]]\n| cinematography = Anastas Michos\n| editing = Peter C. Frank\n| studio  = [[TriStar Pictures]]<br />[[Sony Music Entertainment]]<br />[[Parkwood Entertainment]]\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]] \n| released = {{Film date|2008|11|24|[[Grauman's Egyptian Theatre]]|2008|12|05|United States}}\n| runtime = 109 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $12 million\n| gross = $8.9 million<ref name=\"Box Office Gross\"/>\n}}\n'''''Cadillac Records''''' is a 2008 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[Darnell Martin]]. The film explores the musical era from the early 1940s to the late 1960s, chronicling the life of the influential [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]-based record-company executive [[Leonard Chess]], and a few of the musicians who recorded for [[Chess Records]].\n\nThe film stars [[Adrien Brody]] as [[Leonard Chess]], [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as [[Willie Dixon]], [[Mos Def]] as [[Chuck Berry]], [[Columbus Short]] as [[Little Walter]], [[Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Muddy Waters]], [[Eamonn Walker]] as [[Howlin' Wolf]], and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as [[Etta James]]. The film was released in North America on December 5, 2008 by [[TriStar Pictures]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1947 in Chicago, a [[Judaism|Jewish]] immigrant from [[History of the Jews in Poland|Poland]] and bar owner [[Leonard Chess]] ([[Adrien Brody]]) hires a [[blues]] combo, including [[guitarist]] [[Muddy Waters]] ([[Jeffrey Wright]]) and [[harmonica]] player [[Little Walter]] ([[Columbus Short]]). Waters' and Walter's success leads to Chess opening the doors for black musicians and beginning a new record label in 1950 \u2013 Chess Records. This attracts stars like [[Etta James]] ([[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]), [[Howlin' Wolf]] ([[Eamonn Walker]]) and [[Chuck Berry]] ([[Mos Def]]). Inevitably, business and personal lines blur as the sometimes-turbulent lives of the musicians play out.\n\n==Main cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Adrien Brody]] as [[Leonard Chess]]\n* [[Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Muddy Waters]]\n* [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as [[Etta James]]\n* [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as [[Willie Dixon]]\n* [[Gabrielle Union]] as Geneva Wade\n* [[Columbus Short]] as [[Little Walter]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Chriqui]] as Revetta Chess\n* [[Eamonn Walker]] as [[Howlin' Wolf]]\n* [[Mos Def]] as [[Chuck Berry]]\n* [[Shiloh Fernandez]] as [[Phil Chess]]\n* [[Jay O. Sanders]] as Mr. Feder\n* [[Eric Bogosian]] as [[Alan Freed]]\n* [[Kevin Mambo]] as [[Jimmy Rogers]]\n* Marc Bonan as [[Keith Richards]]\n* [[Tammy Blanchard]] as Isabelle Allen\n* [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] as Hip Hop Artist \n* [[Norman Reedus]] as Chess record engineer\n* [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] as Mississippi DJ (uncredited)\n* [[Elvis Presley]] as Himself (archive footage) (uncredited)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Background==\n[[Leonard Chess]] was the co-founder of the 1950s American [[record label]] [[Chess Records]], located in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. He ran the legendary company with his brother, Phil, through the 1950s and '60s.<ref name=\"Rodriguez\">{{Cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Jayson |title=Beyonc\u00e9 To Portray Legendary Blues Singer Etta James In 'Cadillac Records' |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1581909/beyonce-to-portray-legendary-blues-singer-etta-james-in-cadillac-records/ |work=MTV News |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> The label started selling records from the back of Chess' [[Cadillac]],<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{Cite news |author=Hollywood reporter |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Producing, Starring in 'Cadillac Records' |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20178953,00.html |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> and launched the careers of legendary musical personalities such as [[blues]] singers and [[harmonica]] and [[guitar]] players [[Little Walter]] and [[Muddy Waters]], [[Howlin' Wolf]], [[soul music|soul]] legend [[Etta James]]<ref name=\"Tilly\">{{Cite news |last=Tilly |first=Chris |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Signs to Cadillac Records |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/853/853389p1.html |work=IGN |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> and [[guitarist]] singer-songwriters [[Chuck Berry]] and [[Willie Dixon]].<ref name=\"Simmons\">{{Cite news |last=Simmons |first=Leslie |title=Matt Dillon playing Chess in music movie |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/filmNews/idUSN1527557320071015 |work=Reuters |date=October 15, 2007 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Beyonce Cadillac Records Premiere Party.jpg|thumbnail|[[Beyonc\u00e9]] at the premiere party for the release of the film]]\nThe [[screenplay]] was written by director [[Darnell Martin]].<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> The filming of ''Cadillac Records'' started in February 2008.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Filming locations included [[Louisiana]], [[Mississippi]], and [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1042877/locations|title=Filming locations for ''Cadillac Records'' (2008)|accessdate=August 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225143640/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1042877/locations |archivedate=December 25, 2008 }}</ref> Martin directed the film,<ref name=\"Rodriguez\"/><ref name=\"Tilly\"/> financed by Sony BMG Film.<ref name=\"Simmons\"/> ''Cadillac Records'' was produced by Andrew Lack and Sofia Sondervan,<ref name=\"Variety\"/> and co-executive produced by Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles.<ref name=\"Rodriguez\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nOriginally, [[Matt Dillon]] was slated to play the role of Chess,<ref name=\"Simmons\"/> but the role was ultimately given to [[Academy Award]]-winner [[Adrien Brody]] due to scheduling conflicts with Dillon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20172936,00.html|title=Adrien Brody, Jeffrey Wright in ''Cadillac'|date=January 22, 2008|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=2008-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Early announcements of the cast also included [[Columbus Short]] as [[Little Walter]], [[Golden Globe]] winner [[Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Muddy Waters]],<ref name=\"Rodriguez\"/>  and multi-[[Grammy Award]] winner [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as [[Etta James]]. According to director Martin,  the role of James was written with Beyonc\u00e9 in mind.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/16/arts/music/16ligh.html|title=Pop Music\u2019s Dreamgirl Awakens Her Earthy Side|last=Light|first=Allan|date=November 14, 2008|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2008-11-21}}</ref>\n\nAs production increased, the roster grew to include Canadian actress [[Emmanuelle Chriqui]] as Revetta Chess, [[Tammy Blanchard]] as Isabelle Allen, English actor [[Eamonn Walker]] as Howlin' Wolf, and [[comedian]] [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as [[Willie Dixon]].<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/><ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite news |author=IGN staff |title=Cadillac Cast |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/846/846750p1.html |work=IGN |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103062849/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/846/846750p1.html |archive-date=January 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite news|last=Haves|first=Dade|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979390.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Brody, Wright set to drive 'Cadillac'|date=January 21, 2008|work=Variety|accessdate=2008-03-28|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314185723/http://variety.com/2008/film/markets-festivals/brody-wright-set-to-drive-cadillac-1117979390/|archive-date=14 March 2017}}</ref> Final line ups of the cast also grew to include [[rapper]] [[Mos Def]] as [[Chuck Berry]], and [[Gabrielle Union]] in the role of Geneva Wade, Muddy Waters' common law wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117983173.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|author=Winter Miller|title=Duo drives 'Cadillac'|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 30, 2008|accessdate=2008-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Cadillac Records: Music from the Motion Picture}}\nThe American multi-instrumentalist, songwriter, and [[record producer]] [[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]] produced the soundtrack to the film. He also picked a group of blues musicians, including Billy Flynn (guitar), [[Larry Taylor]] (bass), [[Eddie Taylor Jr.]] (guitar), [[Barrelhouse Chuck]] (piano), [[Kim Wilson]] (harmonica), [[Danny Kortchmar]] (guitar), [[Hubert Sumlin]] (guitar), and Bill Sims (guitar) who, along with Jordan on drums, recorded all of the blues songs used in the film.<ref name=\"Leslie\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046493/beyonce-starring-in-chess-records-film|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Starring In Chess Records Film|last=Simmons|first=Leslie|date=February 20, 2008|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2008-03-30}}</ref>\n\nBeyonc\u00e9 recorded five songs for the soundtrack, including a [[cover version]] of [[Etta James]]' \"[[At Last]]\" which was released on December 2, 2008 as its [[lead single]].<ref name=\"CohenSound\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043534/beyonce-belts-it-out-on-cadillac-soundtrack|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Belts It Out On 'Cadillac' Soundtrack|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=November 11, 2008|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2008-11-12}}</ref> Mos Def, Jeffrey Wright, Columbus Short, and Eamonn Walker recorded songs for the soundtrack, and [[Raphael Saadiq]], Beyonc\u00e9's sister [[Solange Knowles|Solange]], [[Mary Mary]], [[Nas]], [[Buddy Guy]], and [[Elvis Presley]] also appear on the album. The soundtrack was released in single and double-disc editions.<ref name=\"CohenSound\"/>\n\nThe month after the film was released, Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"At Last\" at the inauguration ball of [[Barack Obama]], as he and wife [[Michelle Obama|Michelle]] danced together for the first time as President and First Lady.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Russell |last1=Goldman |first2=Luchina |last2=Fisher |title=At Last! Obama Dances Into History at 10 Balls |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/obamas-dance-inaugural-balls-beyonce/story?id=6694753 |website=ABC News |accessdate=July 19, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118000130/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/obamas-dance-inaugural-balls-beyonce/story?id=6694753#.U8sF-LEhWSo |archive-date=January 18, 2012 |url-status=live |date=January 20, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack spent 48 weeks at number one of the [[Top Blues Albums]].\n\nThe soundtrack was nominated for three 2010 [[Grammy Award]]s in the following categories: [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack Album for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]], Beyonc\u00e9's \"Once in a Lifetime\" for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]] and Beyonc\u00e9's \"At Last\" for [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional R&B Performance|Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance]].\n\n==Release and reception==\nThe film had its [[Film premiere|world premiere]] on November 24, 2008 at the [[Grauman's Egyptian Theatre|Egyptian Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1600243/beyonce-etta-james-and-cadillac-records-stars-come-out-for-movies-premiere/|title=Beyonc\u00e9, Etta James And 'Cadillac Records' Stars Come Out For Movie's Premiere|last=Adler|first=Shawn|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 26, 2008}}</ref> On December 5, 2008, it entered general release in the United States. On its opening weekend, the film opened at Number 9, grossing $3.4 million in 686 cinemas with an $5,023 average.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2008&wknd=49&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results from December 5\u20137, 2008 | publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] | date=December 7, 2008 | accessdate=December 9, 2008}}</ref> When the film left cinemas in January 2009, it had yet to recoup its $12 million budget; it ended its run with a worldwide box office gross of  $8,880,045.<ref name=\"Box Office Gross\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=cadillacrecords.htm|title=Cadillac Records (2008)|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film received mostly positive reviews. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives a score of 67% based on reviews from 123 critics. Its consensus state that \"What ''Cadillac Records'' may lack in originality, it more than makes up for in strong performances and soul-stirring music.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/cadillac_records/ | title=Cadillac Records | publisher= [[Flixster]] | work = Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=2020-02-21}}</ref> Another review aggretator, [[Metacritic]], gave the film a 65% approval rating based on 30 reviews classifying that the film has \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/cadillacrecords | title=Cadillac Records (2008):Reviews | publisher= [[CBS]] | work = Metacritic | accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'' gave the film three stars and stated in his review that \"The film is a fascinating record of the evolution of a black musical style, and the tangled motives of the white men who had an instinct for it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081203/REVIEWS/812039993 | title=Cadillac Records \u2013 Roger Ebert Review | publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref> Elizabeth Weitzman of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' awarded the film three stars and wrote in her review, \"Writer-director Darnell Martin clearly respects the fact that the history of Chess Records is a worthy subject.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2008/12/05/2008-12-05_cadillac_records_takes_a_greatesthits_ap.html | title='Cadillac Records' takes a greatest-hits approach | publisher=New York Daily News | accessdate=2008-12-07 | first=Elizabeth | last=Weitzman | date=December 4, 2008}}</ref> Most critics praised the film for its music, but complained about its script. Jim Harrington of the ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'' praised Beyonc\u00e9's vocal performance and wrote in his review that, \"[[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]' captivating voice and the film's other pluses can't outweigh the glaring omissions from the story line for this critic\" and \"Chess Records deserves, and will hopefully someday get, a better spin than the one delivered by ''Cadillac Records''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/tv/ci_11138574 | title='Cadillac Records': Good music, shaky history | publisher=Mercury News | date=December 5, 2008 | accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition and accolades===\n[[David Edelstein]] of [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]] named it the 4th best film of 2008,<ref name=mctop08/>\nStephanie Zacharek of ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'' named it the 4th best film of 2008,<ref name=mctop08/> and\n[[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' named it the 10th best film of 2008.<ref name=mctop08>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2008/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2008 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100224083805/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2008/toptens.shtml |archivedate=February 24, 2010 }}</ref> During the 2009 award season, Knowles received a [[Satellite Award]] nomination for her portrayal of Etta James.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml |title=2008 13th Annual SATELLITE\u2122 Awards |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=2011-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202035312/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml |archivedate=December 2, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref> Knowles, Amanda Ghost, Scott McFarmon, Ian Dench, James Dring and Jody Street received a [[Golden Globe]] nomination, Best Original Song, for writing \"Once in a Lifetime\"; a song Knowles recorded for the film's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/index.html|title=HFPA \u2013 Nominations and Winners|publisher=Golden Globes|year=2008|accessdate=2011-11-03}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997978.html?categoryId=2773&cs=1|title=Beyonc\u00e9 & Co.|last=Ryder|first=Caroline|date=January 5, 2009|work=Variety|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> The film also garnered seven [[NAACP Image Award]] nominations, which included Outstanding Motion Picture, Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture ([[Jeffrey Wright]]), Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture ([[Cedric the Entertainer]], [[Columbus Short]] and [[Mos Def]]), and Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture (Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naacpimageawards.net/40/nom_movies.php |title=The 40th Annual NAACP Image Awards |publisher=naacpimageawards.net |date=January 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211235604/http://www.naacpimageawards.net/40/nom_movies.php |archivedate=February 11, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] on March 10, 2009, and sold over 130,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"DVD Sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/CADLC-DVD.php|title=Cadillac Records \u2013 DVD Sales \u2013 The Numbers|publisher=The Numbers/|accessdate=2009-04-03}}</ref> To date it has made an estimate of $11,916,737 in sales,<ref name=\"DVD Sales\"/> which coupled with its box office gross helped the film pay back its $12 million budget ('''total gross:''' $20,796,782).\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! width=\"25%\"| Ceremony\n! width=\"45%\"| Category\n! width=\"20%\"| Recipient\n! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| [[African-American Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| [[Jeffrey Wright]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Black Reel Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Black Reel Award: Best Film|Best Film]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Black Reel Award: Best Ensemble|Best Ensemble]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award: Best Director|Best Director]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Darnell Martin]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award: Best Screenplay, Adapted or Original|Best Screenplay, Adapted or Original]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Black Reel Award: Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Jeffrey Wright]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Eamonn Walker]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Mos Def]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award: Best Breakthrough Performance|Best Breakthrough Performance]]\n| [[Columbus Short]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| \"Once In a Lifetime\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Grammy Award]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance|Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance]]\n| \"[[At Last#Beyonc\u00e9 version|At Last]]\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[NAACP Image Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Motion Picture|Outstanding Motion Picture]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture]]\n| [[Jeffrey Wright]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture]]\n| [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture]]\n| [[Cedric the Entertainer]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Columbus Short]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Mos Def]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award|Outstanding Writing in a Motion Picture (Television or Film)]]\n| [[Darnell Martin]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture]]\n| [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 2008]]\n* ''[[Cadillac Records: Music from the Motion Picture]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|film}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.sonypictures.com/movies/cadillacrecords/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1042877|Cadillac Records}}\n* {{Allmovie title|429778|Cadillac Records}}\n* {{mojo title|cadillacrecords|Cadillac Records}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|cadillac_records|Cadillac Records}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''Cadillac Records''\n|list =\n{{Black Reel Award for Outstanding Film}}\n{{Black Reel Award for Outstanding Ensemble}}\n}}\n{{Darnell Martin}}\n\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s musical films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1951]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1956]]\n[[Category:African-American films]]\n[[Category:African-American musical films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about musicians]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American rock music films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darnell Martin]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Films about race and ethnicity]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Terence Blanchard]]\n[[Category:African-American biographical dramas]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of soul musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of folk musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of The Rolling Stones]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2008 musical biopic directed by Darnell Martin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Cadillac Records\n| image = Cadillac records poster.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darnell Martin]]\n| producer = [[Sofia Sondervan]]<br/>Andrew Lack\n| writer = [[Darnell Martin]]\n| narrator = [[Cedric the Entertainer]]\n| starring = [[Adrien Brody]]<br/>[[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]<br />[[Jeffrey Wright]]<!--per poster-->\n| music = [[Terence Blanchard]]<br/>[[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]]\n| cinematography = Anastas Michos\n| editing = Peter C. Frank\n| studio  = [[TriStar Pictures]]<br />[[Sony Music Entertainment]]<br />[[Parkwood Entertainment]]\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]] \n| released = {{Film date|2008|11|24|[[Grauman's Egyptian Theatre]]|2008|12|05|United States}}\n| runtime = 109 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $12 million\n| gross = $8.9 million<ref name=\"Box Office Gross\"/>\n}}\n'''''Cadillac Records''''' is a 2008 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[Darnell Martin]]. The film explores the musical era from the early 1940s to the late 1960s, chronicling the life of the influential [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]-based record-company executive [[Leonard Chess]], and a few of the musicians who recorded for [[Chess Records]].\n\nThe film stars [[Adrien Brody]] as [[Leonard Chess]], [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as [[Willie Dixon]], [[Mos Def]] as [[Chuck Berry]], [[Columbus Short]] as [[Little Walter]], [[Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Muddy Waters]], [[Eamonn Walker]] as [[Howlin' Wolf]], and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as [[Etta James]]. The film was released in North America on December 5, 2008 by [[TriStar Pictures]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1947 in Chicago, a [[Judaism|Jewish]] immigrant from [[History of the Jews in Poland|Poland]] and bar owner [[Leonard Chess]] ([[Adrien Brody]]) hires a [[blues]] combo, including [[guitarist]] [[Muddy Waters]] ([[Jeffrey Wright]]) and [[harmonica]] player [[Little Walter]] ([[Columbus Short]]). Waters' and Walter's success leads to Chess opening the doors for black musicians and beginning a new record label in 1950 \u2013 Chess Records. This attracts stars like: [[Etta James]] ([[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]), [[Howlin' Wolf]] ([[Eamonn Walker]]) and [[Chuck Berry]] ([[Mos Def]]). Inevitably, business and personal lines blur as the sometimes-turbulent lives of the musicians play out. \n\n==Main cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Adrien Brody]] as [[Leonard Chess]]\n* [[Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Muddy Waters]]\n* [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as [[Etta James]]\n* [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as [[Willie Dixon]]\n* [[Gabrielle Union]] as Geneva Wade\n* [[Columbus Short]] as [[Little Walter]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Chriqui]] as Revetta Chess\n* [[Eamonn Walker]] as [[Howlin' Wolf]]\n* [[Mos Def]] as [[Chuck Berry]]\n* [[Shiloh Fernandez]] as [[Phil Chess]]\n* [[Jay O. Sanders]] as Mr. Feder\n* [[Eric Bogosian]] as [[Alan Freed]]\n* [[Kevin Mambo]] as [[Jimmy Rogers]]\n* Marc Bonan as [[Keith Richards]]\n* [[Tammy Blanchard]] as Isabelle Allen\n* [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] as Hip Hop Artist \n* [[Norman Reedus]] as Chess record engineer\n* [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] as Mississippi DJ (uncredited)\n* [[Elvis Presley]] as Himself (archive footage) (uncredited)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Background==\n[[Leonard Chess]] was the co-founder of the 1950s American [[record label]] [[Chess Records]], located in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. He ran the legendary company with his brother, Phil, through the 1950s and '60s.<ref name=\"Rodriguez\">{{Cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Jayson |title=Beyonc\u00e9 To Portray Legendary Blues Singer Etta James In 'Cadillac Records' |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1581909/beyonce-to-portray-legendary-blues-singer-etta-james-in-cadillac-records/ |work=MTV News |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> The label started selling records from the back of Chess' [[Cadillac]],<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{Cite news |author=Hollywood reporter |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Producing, Starring in 'Cadillac Records' |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20178953,00.html |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> and launched the careers of legendary musical personalities such as [[blues]] singers and [[harmonica]] and [[guitar]] players [[Little Walter]] and [[Muddy Waters]], [[Howlin' Wolf]], [[soul music|soul]] legend [[Etta James]]<ref name=\"Tilly\">{{Cite news |last=Tilly |first=Chris |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Signs to Cadillac Records |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/853/853389p1.html |work=IGN |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref> and [[guitarist]] singer-songwriters [[Chuck Berry]] and [[Willie Dixon]].<ref name=\"Simmons\">{{Cite news |last=Simmons |first=Leslie |title=Matt Dillon playing Chess in music movie |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/filmNews/idUSN1527557320071015 |work=Reuters |date=October 15, 2007 |accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Beyonce Cadillac Records Premiere Party.jpg|thumbnail|[[Beyonc\u00e9]] at the premiere party for the release of the film]]\nThe [[screenplay]] was written by director [[Darnell Martin]].<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> The filming of ''Cadillac Records'' started in February 2008.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Filming locations included [[Louisiana]], [[Mississippi]], and [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1042877/locations|title=Filming locations for ''Cadillac Records'' (2008)|accessdate=August 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225143640/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1042877/locations |archivedate=December 25, 2008 }}</ref> Martin directed the film,<ref name=\"Rodriguez\"/><ref name=\"Tilly\"/> financed by Sony BMG Film.<ref name=\"Simmons\"/> ''Cadillac Records'' was produced by Andrew Lack and Sofia Sondervan,<ref name=\"Variety\"/> and co-executive produced by Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles.<ref name=\"Rodriguez\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nOriginally, [[Matt Dillon]] was slated to play the role of Chess,<ref name=\"Simmons\"/> but the role was ultimately given to [[Academy Award]]-winner [[Adrien Brody]] due to scheduling conflicts with Dillon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20172936,00.html|title=Adrien Brody, Jeffrey Wright in ''Cadillac'|date=January 22, 2008|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=2008-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Early announcements of the cast also included [[Columbus Short]] as [[Little Walter]], [[Golden Globe]] winner [[Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Muddy Waters]],<ref name=\"Rodriguez\"/>  and multi-[[Grammy Award]] winner [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as [[Etta James]]. According to director Martin,  the role of James was written with Beyonc\u00e9 in mind.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/16/arts/music/16ligh.html|title=Pop Music\u2019s Dreamgirl Awakens Her Earthy Side|last=Light|first=Allan|date=November 14, 2008|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2008-11-21}}</ref>\n\nAs production increased, the roster grew to include Canadian actress [[Emmanuelle Chriqui]] as Revetta Chess, [[Tammy Blanchard]] as Isabelle Allen, English actor [[Eamonn Walker]] as Howlin' Wolf, and [[comedian]] [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as [[Willie Dixon]].<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/><ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite news |author=IGN staff |title=Cadillac Cast |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/846/846750p1.html |work=IGN |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103062849/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/846/846750p1.html |archive-date=January 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite news|last=Haves|first=Dade|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979390.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Brody, Wright set to drive 'Cadillac'|date=January 21, 2008|work=Variety|accessdate=2008-03-28|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314185723/http://variety.com/2008/film/markets-festivals/brody-wright-set-to-drive-cadillac-1117979390/|archive-date=14 March 2017}}</ref> Final line ups of the cast also grew to include [[rapper]] [[Mos Def]] as [[Chuck Berry]], and [[Gabrielle Union]] in the role of Geneva Wade, Muddy Waters' common law wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117983173.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|author=Winter Miller|title=Duo drives 'Cadillac'|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 30, 2008|accessdate=2008-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Cadillac Records: Music from the Motion Picture}}\nThe American multi-instrumentalist, songwriter, and [[record producer]] [[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]] produced the soundtrack to the film. He also picked a group of blues musicians, including Billy Flynn (guitar), [[Larry Taylor]] (bass), [[Eddie Taylor Jr.]] (guitar), [[Barrelhouse Chuck]] (piano), [[Kim Wilson]] (harmonica), [[Danny Kortchmar]] (guitar), [[Hubert Sumlin]] (guitar), and Bill Sims (guitar) who, along with Jordan on drums, recorded all of the blues songs used in the film.<ref name=\"Leslie\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046493/beyonce-starring-in-chess-records-film|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Starring In Chess Records Film|last=Simmons|first=Leslie|date=February 20, 2008|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2008-03-30}}</ref>\n\nBeyonc\u00e9 recorded five songs for the soundtrack, including a [[cover version]] of [[Etta James]]' \"[[At Last]]\" which was released on December 2, 2008 as its [[lead single]].<ref name=\"CohenSound\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043534/beyonce-belts-it-out-on-cadillac-soundtrack|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Belts It Out On 'Cadillac' Soundtrack|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=November 11, 2008|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2008-11-12}}</ref> Mos Def, Jeffrey Wright, Columbus Short, and Eamonn Walker recorded songs for the soundtrack, and [[Raphael Saadiq]], Beyonc\u00e9's sister [[Solange Knowles|Solange]], [[Mary Mary]], [[Nas]], [[Buddy Guy]], and [[Elvis Presley]] also appear on the album. The soundtrack was released in single and double-disc editions.<ref name=\"CohenSound\"/>\n\nThe month after the film was released, Beyonc\u00e9 performed \"At Last\" at the inauguration ball of [[Barack Obama]], as he and wife [[Michelle Obama|Michelle]] danced together for the first time as President and First Lady.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Russell |last1=Goldman |first2=Luchina |last2=Fisher |title=At Last! Obama Dances Into History at 10 Balls |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/obamas-dance-inaugural-balls-beyonce/story?id=6694753 |website=ABC News |accessdate=July 19, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118000130/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/obamas-dance-inaugural-balls-beyonce/story?id=6694753#.U8sF-LEhWSo |archive-date=January 18, 2012 |url-status=live |date=January 20, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack spent 48 weeks at number one of the [[Top Blues Albums]].\n\nThe soundtrack was nominated for three 2010 [[Grammy Award]]s in the following categories: [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack Album for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]], Beyonc\u00e9's \"Once in a Lifetime\" for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]] and Beyonc\u00e9's \"At Last\" for [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional R&B Performance|Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance]].\n\n==Release and reception==\nThe film had its [[Film premiere|world premiere]] on November 24, 2008 at the [[Grauman's Egyptian Theatre|Egyptian Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1600243/beyonce-etta-james-and-cadillac-records-stars-come-out-for-movies-premiere/|title=Beyonc\u00e9, Etta James And 'Cadillac Records' Stars Come Out For Movie's Premiere|last=Adler|first=Shawn|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 26, 2008}}</ref> On December 5, 2008, it entered general release in the United States. On its opening weekend, the film opened at Number 9, grossing $3.4 million in 686 cinemas with an $5,023 average.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2008&wknd=49&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results from December 5\u20137, 2008 | publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] | date=December 7, 2008 | accessdate=December 9, 2008}}</ref> When the film left cinemas in January 2009, it had yet to recoup its $12 million budget; it ended its run with a worldwide box office gross of  $8,880,045.<ref name=\"Box Office Gross\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=cadillacrecords.htm|title=Cadillac Records (2008)|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film received mostly positive reviews. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives a score of 67% based on reviews from 123 critics. Its consensus state that \"What ''Cadillac Records'' may lack in originality, it more than makes up for in strong performances and soul-stirring music.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/cadillac_records/ | title=Cadillac Records | publisher= [[Flixster]] | work = Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=2020-02-21}}</ref> Another review aggretator, [[Metacritic]], gave the film a 65% approval rating based on 30 reviews classifying that the film has \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/cadillacrecords | title=Cadillac Records (2008):Reviews | publisher= [[CBS]] | work = Metacritic | accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'' gave the film three stars and stated in his review that \"The film is a fascinating record of the evolution of a black musical style, and the tangled motives of the white men who had an instinct for it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081203/REVIEWS/812039993 | title=Cadillac Records \u2013 Roger Ebert Review | publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref> Elizabeth Weitzman of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' awarded the film three stars and wrote in her review, \"Writer-director Darnell Martin clearly respects the fact that the history of Chess Records is a worthy subject.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2008/12/05/2008-12-05_cadillac_records_takes_a_greatesthits_ap.html | title='Cadillac Records' takes a greatest-hits approach | publisher=New York Daily News | accessdate=2008-12-07 | first=Elizabeth | last=Weitzman | date=December 4, 2008}}</ref> Most critics praised the film for its music, but complained about its script. Jim Harrington of the ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'' praised Beyonc\u00e9's vocal performance and wrote in his review that, \"[[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]]' captivating voice and the film's other pluses can't outweigh the glaring omissions from the story line for this critic\" and \"Chess Records deserves, and will hopefully someday get, a better spin than the one delivered by ''Cadillac Records''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/tv/ci_11138574 | title='Cadillac Records': Good music, shaky history | publisher=Mercury News | date=December 5, 2008 | accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition and accolades===\n[[David Edelstein]] of [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]] named it the 4th best film of 2008,<ref name=mctop08/>\nStephanie Zacharek of ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'' named it the 4th best film of 2008,<ref name=mctop08/> and\n[[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' named it the 10th best film of 2008.<ref name=mctop08>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2008/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2008 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100224083805/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2008/toptens.shtml |archivedate=February 24, 2010 }}</ref> During the 2009 award season, Knowles received a [[Satellite Award]] nomination for her portrayal of Etta James.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml |title=2008 13th Annual SATELLITE\u2122 Awards |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=2011-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202035312/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml |archivedate=December 2, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref> Knowles, Amanda Ghost, Scott McFarmon, Ian Dench, James Dring and Jody Street received a [[Golden Globe]] nomination, Best Original Song, for writing \"Once in a Lifetime\"; a song Knowles recorded for the film's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/index.html|title=HFPA \u2013 Nominations and Winners|publisher=Golden Globes|year=2008|accessdate=2011-11-03}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997978.html?categoryId=2773&cs=1|title=Beyonc\u00e9 & Co.|last=Ryder|first=Caroline|date=January 5, 2009|work=Variety|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> The film also garnered seven [[NAACP Image Award]] nominations, which included Outstanding Motion Picture, Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture ([[Jeffrey Wright]]), Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture ([[Cedric the Entertainer]], [[Columbus Short]] and [[Mos Def]]), and Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture (Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naacpimageawards.net/40/nom_movies.php |title=The 40th Annual NAACP Image Awards |publisher=naacpimageawards.net |date=January 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211235604/http://www.naacpimageawards.net/40/nom_movies.php |archivedate=February 11, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] on March 10, 2009, and sold over 130,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"DVD Sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/CADLC-DVD.php|title=Cadillac Records \u2013 DVD Sales \u2013 The Numbers|publisher=The Numbers/|accessdate=2009-04-03}}</ref> To date it has made an estimate of $11,916,737 in sales,<ref name=\"DVD Sales\"/> which coupled with its box office gross helped the film pay back its $12 million budget ('''total gross:''' $20,796,782).\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! width=\"25%\"| Ceremony\n! width=\"45%\"| Category\n! width=\"20%\"| Recipient\n! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| [[African-American Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| [[Jeffrey Wright]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Black Reel Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Black Reel Award: Best Film|Best Film]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Black Reel Award: Best Ensemble|Best Ensemble]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award: Best Director|Best Director]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Darnell Martin]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award: Best Screenplay, Adapted or Original|Best Screenplay, Adapted or Original]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Black Reel Award: Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Jeffrey Wright]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Eamonn Walker]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Mos Def]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award: Best Breakthrough Performance|Best Breakthrough Performance]]\n| [[Columbus Short]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| \"Once In a Lifetime\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Grammy Award]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance|Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance]]\n| \"[[At Last#Beyonc\u00e9 version|At Last]]\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[NAACP Image Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Motion Picture|Outstanding Motion Picture]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture]]\n| [[Jeffrey Wright]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding S